==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smart
<hw>Smart</hw> <pr>(sm⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Smarted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Smarting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>smarten</ets>, AS.
<ets>smeortan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>smarten</ets>, <ets>smerten</ets>,
G. <ets>schmerzen</ets>, OHG. <ets>smerzan</ets>, Dan.
<ets>smerte</ets>, Sw. <ets>sm⟦aum⟧rta</ets>, D. <ets>smart</ets>,
<ets>smert</ets>, a pain, G. <ets>schmerz</ets>, OHG. <ets>smerzo</ets>,
and probably to L. <ets>mordere</ets> to bite; cf. Gr.
<grk>smerdno`s</grk>, <grk>smerdale`os</grk>, terrible, fearful, Skr.
<ets>m⟦rsdot⟧d</ets> to rub, crush. Cf. <er>Morsel</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel a lively, pungent local pain; -- said of some
part of the body as the seat of irritation; <as>as, my finger
<ex>smarts</ex>; these wounds <ex>smart</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au> <au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel a pungent pain of mind; to feel sharp pain
or grief; to suffer; to feel the sting of evil; <as>as, the team is
still <ex>smarting</ex> from its loss of the
championship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No creature <qex>smarts</qex> so little as a fool.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that is surety for a stranger shall <qex>smart</qex> for
it.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xi. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smart</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smart
<hw>Smart</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause a smart in.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A goad that . . . <xex>smarts</xex> the flesh.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>T.
Adams.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smart</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smart
<hw>Smart</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>smerte</ets>. See
<er>Smart</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Quick, pungent,
lively pain; a pricking local pain, as the pain from puncture by
nettles.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In pain's <xex>smart</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Severe, pungent pain of mind; pungent grief; <as>as,
the <ex>smart</ex> of affliction</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To stand 'twixt us and our deserved <qex>smart</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Counsel mitigates the greatest <qex>smart</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fellow who affects smartness, briskness, and
vivacity; a dandy.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<rj><au>Fielding.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Smart money (see below).</def>
<mark>[Canf]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smart</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Smart
<hw>Smart</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Smarter</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Smartest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>smerte</ets>. See
<er>Smart</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Causing a
smart; pungent; pricking; <as>as, a <ex>smart</ex> stroke or
taste</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How <qex>smart</qex> lash that speech doth give my conscience.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Keen; severe; poignant; <as>as, <ex>smart</ex>
pain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Vigorous; sharp; severe.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Smart</xex> skirmishes, in which many fell.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Accomplishing, or able to accomplish, results
quickly; active; sharp; clever.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Efficient; vigorous; brilliant.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
stars shine <xex>smarter</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Marked by acuteness or shrewdness; quick in
suggestion or reply; vivacious; witty; <as>as, a <ex>smart</ex> reply; a
<ex>smart</ex> saying</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who, for the poor renown of being <qex>smart</qex>⟦br⟧
Would leave a sting within a brother's heart?</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sentence or two, . . . which I thought very
<qex>smart</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Pretentious; showy; spruce; <as>as, a <ex>smart</ex>
gown</as>.</def> <-- in modifying dress or appearance, now used in the
sense of "neat, trim", or "stylish, attractive, elegant." -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Brisk; fresh; <as>as, a <ex>smart</ex>
breeze</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Smart money</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Money paid by a
person to buy himself off from some unpleasant engagement or some
painful situation</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>Money allowed
to soldiers or sailors, in the English service, for wounds and injures
received; also, a sum paid by a recruit, previous to being sworn in, to
procure his release from service</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Law)</fld>
<cd>Vindictive or exemplary damages; damages beyond a full compensation
for the actual injury done</cd>. <au>Burrill.</au>
<au>Greenleaf.</au><-- = punitive damages?. (d) (Finance) Knowledgeable
investors or bettors. "The smart money says that technology stocks are
at a peak." --> -- <col><b>Smart ticket</b></col>, <cd>a certificate
given to wounded seamen, entitling them to smart money.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <au>Brande & C.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pungent; poignant; sharp; tart; acute; quick;
lively; brisk; witty; clever; keen; dashy; showy.</syn> --
<usage><er>Smart</er>, <er>Clever</er>. <xex>Smart</xex> has been much
used in New England to describe a person who is intelligent, vigorous,
and active; as, a <xex>smart</xex> young fellow; a <xex>smart</xex>
workman, etc., conciding very nearly with the English sense of
<xex>clever</xex>. The nearest approach to this in England is in such
expressions as, he was <xex>smart</xex> (pungent or witty) in his reply,
etc.; but <xex>smart</xex> and smartness, when applied to persons, more
commonly refer to dress; as, a <xex>smart</xex> appearance; a
<xex>smart</xex> gown, etc.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smarten</ent>⟦br⟧
